## How each required area is covered

**Email** — RFC-compliant `validate_email` with deliverability (DNS/MX) check; NFKC + lowercase normalization; IDN→punycode via `idna` to defeat homograph domains; disposable-domain blocklist; CRLF header-injection guard; 254-char cap.

**Username** — 3–32 length; strict ASCII regex (must start with a letter); no repeated/trailing separators; reserved-word list checked against the homoglyph **skeleton** (so `аdmin` is rejected); offensive-substring filter; unique on `username_skel` so confusable collisions are blocked at the DB.

**Password** — 12-char minimum, **128-byte maximum** (KDF DoS prevention), control-char rejection, 3-of-4 character-class complexity, repeated-char check, breached-password list (note in code: use HIBP k-anonymity in prod), similarity check vs. email-local-part and username. Hashed with **Argon2id** (memory-hard) — never MD5/SHA/plaintext. Password value is *not* normalized so it round-trips on login.

**Security** — Parameterized SQL everywhere; security headers (`nosniff`, `DENY`, CSP, `no-store`); Origin/CSRF check; token-bucket rate limiter with `Retry-After`; `hmac.compare_digest` for timing-safe token comparison; mass-assignment guard rejecting unexpected fields; XSS-defensive display-name filtering (real defense = output encoding at render).

**Edge cases / enumeration** — Uniqueness enforced atomically by DB constraints (handles concurrent signups); the "already registered" path returns the **same 202 body** as success and burns equivalent time via a dummy Argon2 verify; a global **timing floor** flattens fast/slow divergence; whitespace/unicode normalization throughout; `422` returns **every** validation failure with `{field, code, message}`.

**Status codes** — `202` accepted, `400` malformed/extra fields, `403` bad origin, `415` wrong content-type, `422` validation errors, `429` rate-limited, `500` hashing failure.

## Production hardening notes (called out honestly)

- **Rate limiter & breached-password list are in-memory samples.** For real use: Redis-backed limiter (per-IP *and* per-email) and HIBP range API or a local Bloom filter over the Pwned Passwords corpus — never transmit the raw password.
- **`X-Forwarded-For` is only trustworthy behind a proxy you control** (your Nginx setup) — otherwise it's spoofable.
- **Verification email** isn't wired up; the response message assumes you send one (and send an "account already exists" notice on the duplicate path to keep the HTTP response uniform).
- For cookie-based browser flows, add a **double-submit CSRF token** in addition to the Origin check.

